<subSubSection box="[173,1077,1864,1898]" pageId="41" pageNumber="640" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="41.[173,1379,1432,2133]" box="[173,1077,1864,1898]" pageId="41" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[173,407,1864,1898]" pageId="41" pageNumber="640">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
Swarthy Gerbils are nocturnal and crepuscular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="640" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="41.[173,1379,1432,2133]" pageId="41" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[173,889,1904,1938]" pageId="41" pageNumber="640">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
The Swarthy Gerbil is probably a colonial species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="41" pageNumber="640" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="41.[173,1379,1432,2133]" pageId="41" pageNumber="640">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[174,533,1991,2016]" pageId="41" pageNumber="640">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List, but it would be better considered as Data Deficient owing to lack of information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
